ce:section.ce:para:
The optimum conditions of pH, Dep. pot., Dep. time, Pot. Step and Mod. Amp. for DZ detection was determined according to the DOE method. The 5-level designs based on the L25 OA in Minitab software, along with a selection of five factors, have been accomplished (Tables 1 and 2
                        ). The selection of optimal conditions via larger S/N analysis as the best analysis was carried out. According to the analysis for the larger S/N, the software calculates the values of S/N ratio at the optimum condition. The experimental results are in accordance with the test design, and the optimum conditions, as shown in Table 3
                        , are obtained by S/N analysis at high values.

Under the optimal experimental conditions, the analytical performance of the offered sensor has been tested by DPV procedure after adding different DZ concentrations in solution of the BR (pH 3) (Fig. 9
                        ). As it is seen, by increasing DZ concentration, the cathodic peak current increased, with shifting of peak currents to more negative potentials. There were two linear relationships between the DZ concentration and DPV signal for the calibration curve in the range of 0.1–330 µM (inset of Fig. 9). The LOD was calculated 30 nM based on 3Sb/m, where 3Sb is three times the standard deviation of the blank signals, and m is the slope of the calibration curve. Thus, the proposed electrochemical sensor showed a high linearity range by comparable sensitivity with other offered sensors for DZ detection [19-23] (Table 5
                        ). The low LOD can be attributed to the more performed active sites and the large surface area of the applied nanocomposite. Indeed, a combination of independent properties of NMO, GQDs, and CS nanomaterials, led to the eminence of the designed sensor for DZ detection.
